1
00:00:10,680 --> 00:00:13,160
(COCK CROWS)

2
00:00:13,240 --> 00:00:16,080
(SHE HUMS)

3
00:00:23,080 --> 00:00:25,080
(SHE GASPS)

4
00:00:26,840 --> 00:00:32,040
Rory-y-y-y-y-y-y!

5
00:00:37,240 --> 00:00:39,560
Rory, it's starting.

6
00:00:39,640 --> 00:00:41,040
(AMY WAILS)

7
00:00:43,480 --> 00:00:44,320
Argh.

8
00:00:44,400 --> 00:00:46,240
OK.

9
00:00:46,320 --> 00:00:48,120
- OK...
- False alarm.

10
00:00:48,200 --> 00:00:49,920
- Mmm!
- What?

11
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:51,800
Well, I don't know what it feels like.

12
00:00:51,880 --> 00:00:53,560
I've never had a baby before.

13
00:00:53,640 --> 00:00:56,200
- (METALLIC THRUMMING)
- Mmm!

14
00:00:57,840 --> 00:00:59,080
No.

15
00:00:59,160 --> 00:01:03,840
- I know. Leaf blowers. Use a rake!
- No, it's...

16
00:01:06,840 --> 00:01:08,280
I knew.

17
00:01:08,360 --> 00:01:10,440
I just knew.

18
00:01:18,480 --> 00:01:20,720
- Rory!
- Doctor.

19
00:01:20,800 --> 00:01:23,760
- I've crushed your flowers.
- Oh, Amy will kill you.

20
00:01:23,840 --> 00:01:25,640
- Where is she?
- She'll need a bit longer.

21
00:01:25,720 --> 00:01:27,240
Whenever you're ready, Amy.

22
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:31,640
- Oh, wahey!
- Wahey.

23
00:01:31,720 --> 00:01:34,240
- You've swallowed a planet.
- I'm pregnant.

24
00:01:34,320 --> 00:01:37,040
- You're huge.
- Yeah, I'm pregnant.

25
00:01:37,120 --> 00:01:39,440
- Look at you. When worlds collide.
- Doctor, I'm pregnant.

26
00:01:39,520 --> 00:01:42,920
Oh, look at you both. Five years later
and you haven't changed a bit...

27
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:46,760
- apart from age and size.
- It's good to see you, Doctor.

28
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:49,440
Are you pregnant?

29
00:01:57,520 --> 00:01:59,600
Ah, Leadworth.

30
00:01:59,680 --> 00:02:02,360
- Vibrant as ever.
- It's Upper Leadworth, actually.

31
00:02:02,440 --> 00:02:05,120
We've gone slightly upmarket.

32
00:02:05,200 --> 00:02:08,040
- Where is everyone?
- This is busy.

33
00:02:08,120 --> 00:02:09,920
OK, it's quiet.

34
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:13,720
But it's really restful and healthy.

35
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:16,120
Loads of people here
live well into their 90s.

36
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:17,800
DOCTOR: Well, don't let that get you down.

37
00:02:17,880 --> 00:02:19,520
AMY: It's not getting me down.

38
00:02:19,600 --> 00:02:21,440
- (BIRDSONG)
- I wanted to see how you were.

39
00:02:21,520 --> 00:02:24,240
I don't just abandon people
when they leave the TARDIS.

40
00:02:24,360 --> 00:02:28,360
This Time Lord's for life. You don't get
rid of your old pal the Doctor so easily.

41
00:02:28,480 --> 00:02:31,120
- You came here by mistake, didn't you?
- Yeah,

42
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:33,720
bit of a mistake, but look, what a result.

43
00:02:33,800 --> 00:02:36,760
Look at this...bench.
What a nice bench.

44
00:02:36,840 --> 00:02:38,720
What will they think of next?

45
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:49,520
So...what do you do around here
to stave off the, you know...

46
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:52,080
- Boredom?
- ...self-harm?

47
00:02:54,160 --> 00:02:57,200
- We relax.
- (HE MOUTHS)

48
00:02:57,280 --> 00:02:58,800
We live.

49
00:02:58,880 --> 00:03:02,360
- We listen to the birds.
- Yeah, see?

50
00:03:02,440 --> 00:03:04,320
Birds.

51
00:03:04,400 --> 00:03:07,480
- Those are nice.
- We didn't get a lot of time to listen

52
00:03:07,560 --> 00:03:09,800
to birdsong back in the TARDIS days.

53
00:03:09,880 --> 00:03:13,840
- (BIRDSONG GETS LOUDER)
- Oh, blimey! My head's a bit...ooh...

54
00:03:13,920 --> 00:03:16,120
No, you're right,

55
00:03:16,200 --> 00:03:20,080
there wasn't a lot of time
for birdsong back in the good...

56
00:03:22,880 --> 00:03:23,880
...old...

57
00:03:29,840 --> 00:03:35,400
...days. What? No, yes, sorry, what?

58
00:03:35,480 --> 00:03:37,800
Oh, you're OK.

59
00:03:37,920 --> 00:03:41,560
Oh, thank God!
I had a terrible nightmare about you two.

60
00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:43,320
That was scary.

61
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:45,960
Don't ask, you don't want to know.

62
00:03:46,040 --> 00:03:49,000
- You're safe now. That's what counts.
- Oh, OK.

63
00:03:50,040 --> 00:03:55,280
Blimey, never dropped off
like that before. Well, never, really.

64
00:03:55,360 --> 00:03:56,960
I'm getting on a bit, you see.

65
00:03:57,040 --> 00:04:00,320
Don't let the cool gear fool you.
Now, what's wrong with the console?

66
00:04:00,400 --> 00:04:02,640
Red flashing lights...

67
00:04:04,240 --> 00:04:06,720
I bet they mean something.

68
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:10,360
- I also had a kind of dream thing.
- Yeah, so did.

69
00:04:10,440 --> 00:04:13,560
Not a nightmare, though, just...
We were married.

70
00:04:13,640 --> 00:04:15,960
Yeah. In a little village.

71
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:18,440
A sweet little village,
and you were pregnant.

72
00:04:18,520 --> 00:04:20,400
Yes, I was huge. I was a boat.

73
00:04:20,480 --> 00:04:23,040
So you had the same dream, then?

74
00:04:23,120 --> 00:04:25,760
- Exactly the same dream?
- Are you calling me a boat?

75
00:04:25,840 --> 00:04:29,120
- Doctor, you were visiting.
- Yeah, you came to our cottage.

76
00:04:29,240 --> 00:04:32,560
How can we have had the same dream?
It doesn't make any sense.

77
00:04:32,680 --> 00:04:36,720
And you had a nightmare about us.
What happened to us in the nightmare?

78
00:04:36,800 --> 00:04:38,440
It was similar in some aspects.

79
00:04:38,520 --> 00:04:39,920
- Which aspects?
- All of them.

80
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:41,760
- You had the same dream?
- Basically.

81
00:04:41,840 --> 00:04:44,040
- You said it was a nightmare.
- Did I say nightmare?

82
00:04:44,120 --> 00:04:46,840
No. More of a really good...mare.

83
00:04:46,960 --> 00:04:51,320
Look, it doesn't matter.
We all had some kind of psychic episode.

84
00:04:51,400 --> 00:04:53,040
We probably jumped a time track.

85
00:04:53,120 --> 00:04:55,280
- (BIRDSONG)
- Forget it, we're back to reality now.

86
00:04:55,360 --> 00:04:59,040
Doctor, if we're back to reality,
how come I can still hear birds?

87
00:04:59,120 --> 00:05:03,120
Yeah, the same birds.
The same ones we heard in the dream.

88
00:05:03,200 --> 00:05:05,600
Oh. Sorry. Nodded off, stupid.

89
00:05:05,680 --> 00:05:08,200
God, I must be overdoing it.

90
00:05:08,280 --> 00:05:10,360
I was dreaming
we were back on the TARDIS.

91
00:05:10,440 --> 00:05:13,200
- You had the same dream, didn't you?
- Back on the TARDIS,

92
00:05:13,320 --> 00:05:16,160
- weren't we just saying the same thing?
- But we thought this was the dream.

93
00:05:16,240 --> 00:05:18,800
I think so. Why do dreams
have to fade so quickly?

94
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:21,200
- Doctor, what is going on?
- Is this because of you?

95
00:05:21,320 --> 00:05:24,560
- Is this because you've shown up again?
- Listen to me. Trust nothing.

96
00:05:24,640 --> 00:05:27,040
From now on, trust nothing you see,
hear or feel.

97
00:05:27,120 --> 00:05:28,880
But we're awake now.

98
00:05:28,960 --> 00:05:31,320
You thought you were awake
on the TARDIS too.

99
00:05:31,400 --> 00:05:33,080
- But we're home.
- Yeah. You're home.

100
00:05:33,160 --> 00:05:35,680
You're also dreaming.
Trouble is, Rory, Amy, which is which?

101
00:05:35,760 --> 00:05:37,960
Are we flashing forwards...

102
00:05:38,040 --> 00:05:41,320
or backwards?

103
00:05:41,400 --> 00:05:42,880
Hold on tight.

104
00:05:45,880 --> 00:05:47,560
This is going to be a tricky one.

105
00:06:24,200 --> 00:06:26,000
(AMY GASPS)

106
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:30,160
This is bad. I don't like this.

107
00:06:30,240 --> 00:06:31,520
Argh!

108
00:06:32,880 --> 00:06:35,520
Never use force.
You just embarrass yourself.

109
00:06:35,600 --> 00:06:38,360
Unless you're cross, in which case...
always use force.

110
00:06:38,440 --> 00:06:41,760
- Shall I run and get the manual?
- I threw it in a supernova.

111
00:06:41,840 --> 00:06:43,920
AMY: You threw the manual
in a supernova?

112
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:45,800
- Why?
- Because I disagreed with it.

113
00:06:45,880 --> 00:06:47,560
Stop talking to me when I'm cross.

114
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:49,880
OK, but whatever's wrong
with the TARDIS,

115
00:06:49,960 --> 00:06:52,080
is that what caused us
to dream about the future?

116
00:06:52,200 --> 00:06:55,440
- If we were dreaming of the future...
- Of course we were. We were in Leadworth.

117
00:06:55,520 --> 00:06:57,360
- Upper Leadworth.
- Yeah,

118
00:06:57,440 --> 00:06:59,680
and we could still be in Upper Leadworth,

119
00:06:59,760 --> 00:07:01,600
- dreaming of this. Don't you get it?
- No.

120
00:07:01,680 --> 00:07:03,720
OK, no, this is real.
I'm definitely awake.

121
00:07:03,800 --> 00:07:06,680
And you thought you were awake
when you were all elephanty.

122
00:07:06,760 --> 00:07:08,840
Hey, pregnant.

123
00:07:08,920 --> 00:07:11,520
You could be giving birth right now.
This could be the dream.

124
00:07:11,600 --> 00:07:14,520
I told you - trust nothing we see
or hear or feel. Look around you.

125
00:07:14,600 --> 00:07:18,760
Examine everything. Look for all
the details that don't ring true.

126
00:07:18,840 --> 00:07:22,240
OK, we're in a spaceship that's bigger
on the inside than the outside.

127
00:07:22,360 --> 00:07:26,560
- With a bow tie-wearing alien.
- Maybe "what rings true" isn't so simple.

128
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:28,480
Valid point.

129
00:07:28,560 --> 00:07:31,680
(TARDIS POWERS DOWN)

130
00:07:36,760 --> 00:07:38,720
It's dead.

131
00:07:38,800 --> 00:07:40,880
We're in a dead time machine.

132
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:43,680
(BIRDSONG)

133
00:07:46,120 --> 00:07:48,040
Remember - this is real,

134
00:07:48,120 --> 00:07:51,080
but when we wake up in the other place,
remember how real this feels.

135
00:07:51,160 --> 00:07:53,800
It /sreal. I know it's real.

136
00:07:53,880 --> 00:07:55,560
(BIRDSONG CONTINUES)

137
00:07:56,960 --> 00:07:58,360
(BELL TOLLS)

138
00:08:03,800 --> 00:08:07,240
OK. This is the real one,
definitely this one. It's all solid.

139
00:08:07,320 --> 00:08:08,880
It felt solid in the TARDIS too.

140
00:08:08,960 --> 00:08:11,240
You can't spot a dream
while you're having it.

141
00:08:11,320 --> 00:08:12,560
What are you doing?

142
00:08:12,640 --> 00:08:16,400
Looking for motion blur, pixilation.
It could be a computer simulation.

143
00:08:16,480 --> 00:08:19,880
- I don't think so, though.
- Hello, Doctor.

144
00:08:19,960 --> 00:08:22,240
- Hello.
- Hi.

145
00:08:22,320 --> 00:08:24,480
- You're a doctor?
- Yeah.

146
00:08:24,560 --> 00:08:26,480
And, unlike you,
I've actually passed some exams.

147
00:08:26,560 --> 00:08:29,280
A doctor, not a nurse.
Just like you've always dreamed.

148
00:08:29,360 --> 00:08:30,880
- How interesting.
- What is?

149
00:08:30,960 --> 00:08:34,880
Your dream wife, your dream job,
probably your dream baby.

150
00:08:34,960 --> 00:08:37,560
- Maybe this is your dream.
- It's Amy's dream too.

151
00:08:37,640 --> 00:08:40,440
- Isn't it, Amy?
- Yes. Course it is, yeah.

152
00:08:40,520 --> 00:08:42,960
- What's that?
- Old people's home.

153
00:08:49,040 --> 00:08:51,520
You said everyone here
lives to their 90s.

154
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:54,240
There's something
that doesn't make sense.

155
00:08:54,320 --> 00:08:56,560
Let's go and poke it with a stick.

156
00:08:59,160 --> 00:09:01,880
(SIGHS) Can we not do the running thing?

157
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:07,120
WOMAN: Oh, hello, Dr Williams.

158
00:09:07,200 --> 00:09:09,120
WOMAN 2: Hello, Rory, love.

159
00:09:09,200 --> 00:09:11,040
Hello, Mrs Poggit. How's your hip?

160
00:09:11,120 --> 00:09:15,840
- A bit stiff.
- Oh, easy, D-96 compound, plus...

161
00:09:15,920 --> 00:09:17,480
No, you don't have that yet, forget that.

162
00:09:17,560 --> 00:09:19,160
Who's your friend?

163
00:09:19,240 --> 00:09:21,400
A junior doctor?

164
00:09:21,480 --> 00:09:23,240
- Yes.
- Can I borrow you?

165
00:09:23,320 --> 00:09:25,240
You're the size of my grandson.

166
00:09:25,320 --> 00:09:26,480
Er...

167
00:09:27,480 --> 00:09:30,880
Slightly keen to move on.
Freak psychic schism to sort out.

168
00:09:33,320 --> 00:09:36,440
You're incredibly old, aren't you?

169
00:09:41,640 --> 00:09:43,160
(BIRDSONG)

170
00:09:47,720 --> 00:09:50,120
OK, I hate this, Doctor. Stop it.

171
00:09:50,200 --> 00:09:52,400
Because this is definitely real,
it's definitely this one.

172
00:09:52,480 --> 00:09:55,360
- I keep saying that, don't I?
- It's bloody cold.

173
00:09:55,440 --> 00:09:57,280
- The heating's off.
- The heating's off(!)

174
00:09:57,360 --> 00:09:59,920
Yeah. Put on a jumper.
That's what I always do.

175
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:02,720
Yes, sorry about Mrs Poggit.
She's so lovely, though.

176
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:06,200
Oh, I wouldn't believe
her nice old lady act if I were you.

177
00:10:06,280 --> 00:10:07,320
What do you mean, "act"?

178
00:10:07,400 --> 00:10:11,040
Everything's off, sensors, core power.
We're drifting.

179
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:16,160
The scanner's down so we can't even
see out. We could be anywhere.

180
00:10:16,240 --> 00:10:19,440
Someone, something,
is overriding my controls.

181
00:10:19,520 --> 00:10:22,360
MAN: Well, that took a while.

182
00:10:22,440 --> 00:10:25,720
Honestly, I'd heard such good things.

183
00:10:25,800 --> 00:10:28,880
"Last of the Time Lords."
"The Oncoming Storm."

184
00:10:28,960 --> 00:10:31,800
"Him in the bow tie.”" (CHUCKLES)

185
00:10:31,880 --> 00:10:33,760
How did you get into my TARDIS?

186
00:10:33,840 --> 00:10:36,040
- What are you?
- What shall we call me?

187
00:10:36,120 --> 00:10:40,080
Well, if you're the Time Lord,
let's call me the Dream Lord.

188
00:10:40,160 --> 00:10:43,800
- Nice look.
- This? No, I'm not convinced.

189
00:10:43,880 --> 00:10:45,680
Bow ties?

190
00:10:50,200 --> 00:10:51,680
Interesting.

191
00:10:51,720 --> 00:10:56,040
I'd love to be impressed, but Dream Lord -
it's in the name, isn't it?

192
00:10:56,120 --> 00:10:59,800
Spooky, not quite there.

193
00:10:59,880 --> 00:11:02,720
- And yet very much here.
- I'll do the talking, thank you.

194
00:11:02,800 --> 00:11:06,480
Amy, want to take a guess
at what...that is?

195
00:11:06,560 --> 00:11:09,480
- Um...Dream Lord. He creates dreams.
- Dreams, delusions,

196
00:11:09,600 --> 00:11:11,920
- cheap tricks.
- And what about the gooseberry here?

197
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:13,640
Does he get a guess?

198
00:11:13,760 --> 00:11:17,560
Listen, mate, if anyone's the gooseberry
around here, it's the Doctor.

199
00:11:17,640 --> 00:11:20,880
Well, now, there's a delusion
I'm not responsible for.

200
00:11:20,960 --> 00:11:23,080
No, he is. Isn't he, Amy?

201
00:11:23,160 --> 00:11:25,160
Oh, Amy, have to sort your men out.

202
00:11:25,240 --> 00:11:26,680
Choose, even.

203
00:11:26,760 --> 00:11:29,800
I have chosen. Of course I've chosen.

204
00:11:31,520 --> 00:11:34,320
- It's you, stupid.
- Oh, good, thanks.

205
00:11:35,440 --> 00:11:37,680
You can't fool me.
I've seen your dreams.

206
00:11:37,760 --> 00:11:41,640
Some of them twice, Amy.
Blimey! I'd blush...

207
00:11:41,720 --> 00:11:44,600
if I had a blood supply or a real face.

208
00:11:46,240 --> 00:11:48,520
Where did you pick up
this cheap cabaret act?

209
00:11:48,600 --> 00:11:51,480
- Me? Oh, you're on shaky ground.
- Am I?

210
00:11:51,600 --> 00:11:55,760
If you had any more tawdry quirks,
you could open up a Tawdry Quirk Shop.

211
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:58,840
The madcap vehicle,
the cockamamie hair,

212
00:11:58,920 --> 00:12:03,040
the clothes designed by
a first-year fashion student...

213
00:12:03,120 --> 00:12:05,880
I'm surprised you haven't got
a little purple space dog,

214
00:12:05,960 --> 00:12:09,560
just to ram home
what an intergalactic wag you are.

215
00:12:10,960 --> 00:12:12,760
Where was I?

216
00:12:12,840 --> 00:12:16,880
- Er...you were...
- I know where I was.

217
00:12:16,960 --> 00:12:19,840
So here's your challenge.
Two worlds.

218
00:12:19,960 --> 00:12:24,280
Here in the time machine,
and there in the village that time forgot.

219
00:12:24,360 --> 00:12:28,200
One is real, the other's fake.
And just to make it more interesting,

220
00:12:28,280 --> 00:12:31,720
you're going to face in both worlds
a deadly danger.

221
00:12:31,800 --> 00:12:36,680
But only one of the dangers is real.
Tweet, tweet. Time to sleep.

222
00:12:36,760 --> 00:12:42,400
- (BIRDSONG)
- Oh. Or are you waking up?

223
00:12:52,600 --> 00:12:54,960
DREAM LORD: Oh, this is bad.
This is very, very bad.

224
00:12:55,040 --> 00:12:57,160
Look at this X-ray.

225
00:12:57,240 --> 00:12:59,720
Your brain is completely see-through.

226
00:12:59,800 --> 00:13:02,320
But then, I've always been able
to see through you, Doctor.

227
00:13:02,400 --> 00:13:06,240
- Always? What do you mean, always?
- Now, then. The prognosis is this.

228
00:13:06,320 --> 00:13:08,920
If you die in the dream,
you wake up in reality.

229
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:10,760
Healthy recovery in next to no time.

230
00:13:10,880 --> 00:13:13,960
- Ask what happens if you die in reality.
- What happens?

231
00:13:14,040 --> 00:13:17,120
You die, stupid.
That's why it's called reality.

232
00:13:17,200 --> 00:13:20,240
Have you met the Doctor before?
Do you know him? Doctor, does he?

233
00:13:20,320 --> 00:13:23,040
Now, don't get jealous.
He's been around, our boy.

234
00:13:23,120 --> 00:13:26,160
But never mind that.
You've got a world to choose.

235
00:13:26,240 --> 00:13:28,880
One reality was always
too much for you, Doctor.

236
00:13:28,960 --> 00:13:31,080
Take two and call me in the morning.

237
00:13:32,360 --> 00:13:35,000
OK, I don't like him.

238
00:13:35,080 --> 00:13:36,840
- Who is he?
- I don't know.

239
00:13:36,920 --> 00:13:38,080
It's a big universe.

240
00:13:38,160 --> 00:13:39,760
Why is he doing this?

241
00:13:39,840 --> 00:13:41,960
Maybe because he has no physical form.

242
00:13:42,040 --> 00:13:45,400
That gets you down after a while,
so he's taking it out on folk like us

243
00:13:45,480 --> 00:13:47,040
who can touch and eat and feel.

244
00:13:47,160 --> 00:13:50,440
RORY: What does he mean, "deadly danger"?
Nothing deadly has ever happened here.

245
00:13:50,520 --> 00:13:53,560
- A bit of natural wastage, obviously.
- They've all gone.

246
00:13:53,640 --> 00:13:56,280
They've all gone.

247
00:14:03,320 --> 00:14:05,760
Stop. You two, over there.

248
00:14:11,440 --> 00:14:14,920
Come on. We're going up to the castle now.
All of you, come on.

249
00:14:16,080 --> 00:14:19,240
- Why would they leave?
- And what did you mean about Mrs Poggit's

250
00:14:19,320 --> 00:14:21,440
- "nice old lady act"?
- One of my tawdry quirks.

251
00:14:21,520 --> 00:14:23,760
Sniffing out things
that aren't what they seem.

252
00:14:23,840 --> 00:14:25,000
So come on, let's think.

253
00:14:25,080 --> 00:14:27,440
The mechanics of this reality split
we're stuck in...

254
00:14:27,520 --> 00:14:30,480
Time asleep exactly matches
time in our dream world,

255
00:14:30,600 --> 00:14:33,440
- unlike in conventional dreams.
- And we're dreaming the same dream.

256
00:14:33,560 --> 00:14:37,240
Yes, sort of communal trance, very rare.
I'm sure there's a dream giveaway, a tell.

257
00:14:37,320 --> 00:14:42,520
But my mind isn't working because...
(SHOUTING) ...this village is so dull.

258
00:14:42,600 --> 00:14:44,920
- I'm slowing down, like you two have.
- Oh!

259
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:46,440
Oow!

260
00:14:46,520 --> 00:14:48,960
Really. (SCREAMING) Ow!

261
00:14:49,040 --> 00:14:51,920
- It's coming.
- OK. You're a doctor. Help her.

262
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:53,920
- You're a doctor!
- It's OK, we're doctors.

263
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:56,520
- What do we do?
- (AMY PANTS)

264
00:14:56,600 --> 00:14:58,040
OK, it's not coming.

265
00:14:58,120 --> 00:14:59,680
- What?
- This is my life now,

266
00:14:59,760 --> 00:15:01,760
and it just turned you white as a sheet.

267
00:15:01,840 --> 00:15:05,040
So don't you call it dull again, ever. OK?

268
00:15:05,120 --> 00:15:07,120
- Sorry.
- Yeah.

269
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:35,560
Now, we all know
there's an elephant in the room.

270
00:15:35,640 --> 00:15:38,120
I have to be this size,
I'm having a baby.

271
00:15:38,200 --> 00:15:40,200
No, no. The hormones seem real, but no.

272
00:15:40,280 --> 00:15:42,600
Is nobody going to mention
Rory's ponytail?

273
00:15:44,920 --> 00:15:46,760
You hold him down, I'll cut it off.

274
00:15:46,840 --> 00:15:48,480
This from the man in the bow tie.

275
00:15:48,560 --> 00:15:50,040
Bow ties are cool.

276
00:15:54,320 --> 00:15:58,960
I don't know about you, but I wouldn't
hire Mrs Poggit as a babysitter.

277
00:16:05,280 --> 00:16:07,680
What's she doing?

278
00:16:07,760 --> 00:16:09,880
What does she want?

279
00:16:09,960 --> 00:16:12,360
(BIRDSONG)

280
00:16:13,440 --> 00:16:16,080
Oh, no, here we go.

281
00:16:16,520 --> 00:16:17,720
It's really cold.

282
00:16:17,800 --> 00:16:20,640
- Have you got any warm clothing?
- What does it matter if we're cold?

283
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:23,120
We have to know what she's up to.

284
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:25,680
Sorry. Sorry. Um...

285
00:16:25,760 --> 00:16:28,520
There should be some stuff
down there, have a look.

286
00:16:48,640 --> 00:16:50,600
I want the other life...

287
00:16:50,720 --> 00:16:56,600
you know, where we're happy and settled
and about to have a baby.

288
00:16:56,680 --> 00:16:59,480
But don't you wonder,
if that life is real,

289
00:16:59,560 --> 00:17:01,600
then why would we give up all this?

290
00:17:01,680 --> 00:17:03,160
Why would anyone?

291
00:17:03,240 --> 00:17:05,920
Because we're going to freeze to death?

292
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:07,960
The Doctor'll fix it.

293
00:17:09,240 --> 00:17:10,280
OK.

294
00:17:10,360 --> 00:17:13,120
Because we're going to get married?

295
00:17:13,240 --> 00:17:17,360
- Huh?
- (GIGGLING) But we can still get married.

296
00:17:17,440 --> 00:17:20,360
- Some day.
- You don't want to any more.

297
00:17:20,440 --> 00:17:24,000
- I thought you'd chosen me, not him.
- You are always so insecure.

298
00:17:24,080 --> 00:17:27,200
- You ran off with another man.
- Not in that way.

299
00:17:27,280 --> 00:17:30,760
- It was the night before our wedding!
- We're in a time machine.

300
00:17:30,840 --> 00:17:33,120
It'll be the night before our wedding
for as long as we want.

301
00:17:35,360 --> 00:17:37,320
We have to grow up eventually.

302
00:17:38,400 --> 00:17:39,800
Says who?

303
00:17:44,920 --> 00:17:47,400
Ah, Rory, wind.

304
00:17:47,480 --> 00:17:50,040
Amy, could you attach this
to the monitor, please?

305
00:17:50,120 --> 00:17:52,520
I was promised amazing worlds.

306
00:17:52,600 --> 00:17:56,400
Instead I get duff central heating
and a weird, kitcheny, wind-up device.

307
00:17:56,480 --> 00:17:58,240
DOCTOR: It's a generator. Get winding.

308
00:17:58,320 --> 00:18:01,200
- AMY: It's not enough.
- DOCTOR: Rory, wind.

309
00:18:01,280 --> 00:18:04,080
Why is the Dream Lord
picking on you? Why us?

310
00:18:04,160 --> 00:18:06,200
(ELECTRONIC BUZZ)

311
00:18:11,200 --> 00:18:12,480
Where are we?

312
00:18:12,560 --> 00:18:15,920
- We're in trouble.
- What is that?

313
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:19,400
A star. A cold star.

314
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:27,680
That's why we're freezing.
It's not a heating malfunction.

315
00:18:27,760 --> 00:18:29,480
We're drifting towards a cold sun.

316
00:18:29,560 --> 00:18:31,480
There's our deadly danger
for this version of reality.

317
00:18:31,600 --> 00:18:35,400
So this must be the dream. There's
no such thing as a cold star. Stars burn.

318
00:18:35,480 --> 00:18:38,280
- So's this one. It's just burning cold.
- Is that possible?

319
00:18:38,400 --> 00:18:41,920
I can't know everything.
Why does everybody expect me to, always?

320
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:44,200
OK, this is something
you haven't seen before.

321
00:18:44,280 --> 00:18:46,320
So does that mean this is the dream?

322
00:18:46,400 --> 00:18:48,120
I don't know.

323
00:18:48,200 --> 00:18:52,800
But there it is, and I'd say we've got
about 14 minutes until we crash into it.

324
00:18:52,880 --> 00:18:54,320
But that's not a problem.

325
00:18:54,400 --> 00:18:56,280
Because you know
how to get us out of this?

326
00:18:56,360 --> 00:18:59,120
- Because we'll have frozen to death.
- Then what are we going to do?

327
00:18:59,200 --> 00:19:01,040
Stay calm. Don't get sucked in to it,

328
00:19:01,120 --> 00:19:03,880
because this just might be
the battle we have to lose.

329
00:19:03,960 --> 00:19:07,880
- Oh, this is so you, isn't it?
- What?

330
00:19:07,960 --> 00:19:10,120
What? A weird new star,
14 minutes left to live

331
00:19:10,200 --> 00:19:12,680
and only one man to save the day, huh?

332
00:19:12,760 --> 00:19:14,720
I just wanted a nice village
and a family.

333
00:19:14,800 --> 00:19:18,040
Oh, dear, Doctor.
Dissent in the ranks.

334
00:19:18,120 --> 00:19:20,240
There was an old doctor from Gallifrey,

335
00:19:20,320 --> 00:19:23,000
Who ended up throwing his life away.

336
00:19:23,080 --> 00:19:26,080
- He let down his friends and...
- (BIRDSONG)

337
00:19:26,160 --> 00:19:29,960
Oh, no. We've run out of time.

338
00:19:30,040 --> 00:19:32,680
Don't spend too long there,

339
00:19:32,760 --> 00:19:34,400
or you'll, um...

340
00:19:34,480 --> 00:19:36,720
catch your death here.

341
00:19:39,720 --> 00:19:41,240
Where have the children gone?

342
00:19:41,320 --> 00:19:45,520
Don't know. Playtime's probably over.
Ah! You see?

343
00:19:45,600 --> 00:19:47,480
This is the real one. I just feel it.
Don't you feel it?

344
00:19:47,560 --> 00:19:52,720
- I feel it both places.
- I feel it here. It's just so...

345
00:19:52,800 --> 00:19:55,160
tranquil and relaxed.

346
00:19:55,240 --> 00:19:58,240
Nothing bad could ever happen here.

347
00:19:59,200 --> 00:20:00,800
Not really me, though, is it?

348
00:20:00,880 --> 00:20:03,160
Would I be happy settling down
in a place with a pub,

349
00:20:03,240 --> 00:20:06,960
two shops and a really bad amateur
dramatic society? I got pregnant

350
00:20:07,040 --> 00:20:09,200
so I don't have to see them
doing Oklahoma!

351
00:20:09,280 --> 00:20:12,560
Doctor, what are you doing?
And what are those piles of dust?

352
00:20:17,120 --> 00:20:19,840
Playtime's definitely over.

353
00:20:19,920 --> 00:20:21,800
Oh, my God!

354
00:20:23,840 --> 00:20:25,920
What happened to them?

355
00:20:33,800 --> 00:20:35,840
I think they did.

356
00:20:35,920 --> 00:20:38,840
- AMY: They're just old people.
- No.

357
00:20:38,920 --> 00:20:41,400
They're very old people.

358
00:20:41,480 --> 00:20:45,120
Sorry, Rory, I don't think you're
what's been keeping them alive.

359
00:20:48,960 --> 00:20:53,480
Hello, peasants!
What's this? Attack of the old people?

360
00:20:53,560 --> 00:20:55,040
Oh, that's ridiculous.

361
00:20:55,080 --> 00:20:58,080
This has got to be the dream, hasn't it?
What do you think, Amy?

362
00:20:58,160 --> 00:21:01,200
Let's all jump under a bus
and wake up in the TARDIS. You first!

363
00:21:01,280 --> 00:21:02,920
- Leave her alone!
- Do that again.

364
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:05,120
I love it when he does that -

365
00:21:05,200 --> 00:21:08,840
- tall, dark hero, "Leave her alone!"
- Just leave her!

366
00:21:08,920 --> 00:21:12,080
Yes, you're not quite so impressive.
But I know where your heart lies,

367
00:21:12,160 --> 00:21:13,800
- don't I, Amy Pond?
- Shut up!

368
00:21:13,880 --> 00:21:18,000
- Just shut up and leave me alone.
- But listen, you're in there.

369
00:21:18,120 --> 00:21:22,600
Loves a redhead, our naughty Doctor.
Has he told you about Elizabeth the First?

370
00:21:22,720 --> 00:21:26,800
- Well, she thought she was the first... -
Drop it, all of it. I know who you are.

371
00:21:26,920 --> 00:21:30,200
- Course you don't.
- Course I do. No idea how you're here,

372
00:21:30,320 --> 00:21:33,760
but there's only one person in the
universe who hates me as much as you do.

373
00:21:35,680 --> 00:21:40,400
Never mind me.
Maybe you should worry about them.

374
00:21:49,320 --> 00:21:51,160
- Hi.
- Hello.

375
00:21:51,280 --> 00:21:54,760
We were wondering where you went.
To get reinforcements, by the look of it.

376
00:21:54,880 --> 00:21:58,360
- Are you all right? You look a bit tense.
- Hello, Mr Nainby.

377
00:21:58,440 --> 00:22:00,240
- Rory...
- Mr Nainby ran the sweet shop.

378
00:22:00,320 --> 00:22:01,960
He used to slip me the odd free toffee.

379
00:22:02,040 --> 00:22:03,560
Did I not say thank you?

380
00:22:03,640 --> 00:22:05,240
Whoa!

381
00:22:06,600 --> 00:22:11,360
- How did he do that?!
- He's not himself. Don't get comfortable.

382
00:22:11,440 --> 00:22:13,960
- You may have to run. Fast.
- Can't we just talk to them?!

383
00:22:18,160 --> 00:22:21,200
- There is an eye in her mouth!
- There's a whole creature inside her.

384
00:22:21,280 --> 00:22:24,560
Inside all of them. They've been there
for years, living and waiting.

385
00:22:25,880 --> 00:22:30,280
That is disgusting! They're not going to
be peeping out of anywhere else, are they?

386
00:22:31,760 --> 00:22:34,720
Run! ...OK, leave them.
Talk to me. Talk to me.

387
00:22:34,800 --> 00:22:39,600
You are Eknodines, a proud, ancient race.
You're better than this.

388
00:22:39,680 --> 00:22:43,080
Why are you hiding away here?
Why aren't you at home?

389
00:22:43,160 --> 00:22:46,160
- We were driven from our pl...
- Planet by upstart neighbours.

390
00:22:46,240 --> 00:22:48,080
- So we've...
- Been living here inside the bodies

391
00:22:48,160 --> 00:22:49,960
of old humans for years.

392
00:22:50,040 --> 00:22:52,160
No wonder they live so long,
you're keeping them alive.

393
00:22:52,240 --> 00:22:54,040
We were humbled and destroyed.

394
00:22:54,120 --> 00:22:56,560
Now we will do the same to others.

395
00:22:56,640 --> 00:22:59,280
OK, makes sense, I suppose.
Credible enough.

396
00:22:59,360 --> 00:23:01,360
- Could be real.
- Morning.

397
00:23:01,440 --> 00:23:02,480
(SHRIEKING)

398
00:23:05,600 --> 00:23:07,280
You need to leave this planet.

399
00:23:07,360 --> 00:23:09,360
(SHRIEKING)

400
00:23:10,920 --> 00:23:13,800
Wait! Stop! (PANTING)

401
00:23:15,360 --> 00:23:19,040
After all I've done
for the over-70s in this village.

402
00:23:20,480 --> 00:23:23,520
OK, this is crazy. She loves me,
I fixed her depression.

403
00:23:23,600 --> 00:23:26,080
- She's just a little old lady.
- Mrs Hamill,

404
00:23:26,160 --> 00:23:27,880
we don't understand...

405
00:23:32,280 --> 00:23:34,760
I'll deal with this one, Chubs. Now...

406
00:23:44,480 --> 00:23:45,640
I can't hit her.

407
00:23:45,720 --> 00:23:47,720
Whack her!

408
00:24:00,400 --> 00:24:02,760
(SHE PANTS)

409
00:24:02,840 --> 00:24:04,400
We just ran away.

410
00:24:05,520 --> 00:24:10,480
We just abandoned the Doctor.
Don't ever call me Chubs again. (PANTS)

411
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:14,000
We don't see him for years, and somehow
we don't really connect any more,

412
00:24:14,120 --> 00:24:17,280
- then...then he takes the bullet for us.
- Hey, he'll be fine.

413
00:24:17,360 --> 00:24:19,800
You know the Doctor. He's Mr Cool.

414
00:24:20,240 --> 00:24:21,880
(BIRDSONG)

415
00:24:29,400 --> 00:24:30,960
(BELL RINGS)

416
00:24:34,120 --> 00:24:36,640
Oh, I love a good butcher's, don't you?

417
00:24:36,720 --> 00:24:40,200
We've got to use these places
or they'll shut down.

418
00:24:40,280 --> 00:24:44,960
Oh, but you're probably a vegetarian,
you big, flop-haired wuss.

419
00:24:45,040 --> 00:24:46,680
Oh, pipe down. I'm busy.

420
00:24:46,760 --> 00:24:48,920
- Maybe you need a little sleep.
- (BIRDSONG)

421
00:24:53,320 --> 00:24:54,680
Oh, wait a moment -

422
00:24:54,760 --> 00:24:58,160
if you fall asleep here,
several dozen angry pensioners

423
00:24:58,240 --> 00:25:01,240
will destroy you
with their horrible eye thingies.

424
00:25:01,320 --> 00:25:04,040
- (BIRDSONG GETS LOUDER)
- Fingers in the ear?

425
00:25:04,120 --> 00:25:07,400
Brilliant! What's next? Shouting "boo"?

426
00:25:07,480 --> 00:25:10,640
Come in. Come in.

427
00:25:10,720 --> 00:25:14,720
Yes, we've got lots at sfeak here
this week. Lots at sfeak.

428
00:25:14,800 --> 00:25:16,760
- Get it?
- (LOUD BIRDSONG)

429
00:25:16,840 --> 00:25:18,880
Are these jokes wasted on you?

430
00:25:21,720 --> 00:25:23,680
Wait, wait.

431
00:25:23,760 --> 00:25:27,880
- Stop...
- Oh! Oh, I can't watch.

432
00:25:39,360 --> 00:25:41,480
(SHIVERING) Ah, it's colder.

433
00:25:41,560 --> 00:25:44,800
The three of us have to agree, now,
which is the dream.

434
00:25:44,880 --> 00:25:46,560
- It's this, here.
- He could be right.

435
00:25:46,640 --> 00:25:48,160
The science is all wrong here.

436
00:25:48,240 --> 00:25:49,680
- Burning ice?
- No, no, no.

437
00:25:49,760 --> 00:25:52,360
Ice can burn, sofas can read -
it's a big universe.

438
00:25:52,440 --> 00:25:54,720
We have to agree which battle to lose.
All of us, now.

439
00:25:54,800 --> 00:25:56,400
OK, which world do you think is real?

440
00:25:56,480 --> 00:25:58,200
- This one.
- No. The other one.

441
00:25:58,280 --> 00:26:00,360
Yeah, but are we disagreeing
or competing?

442
00:26:00,440 --> 00:26:01,840
Competing? Over what?

443
00:26:04,800 --> 00:26:06,520
Nine minutes till impact.

444
00:26:06,600 --> 00:26:08,080
AMY: What temperature is it?

445
00:26:08,160 --> 00:26:10,800
Outside? How many noughts
have you got? Inside?

446
00:26:10,880 --> 00:26:13,800
I don't know, but I can't feel my feet
and...other parts.

447
00:26:13,920 --> 00:26:17,320
- I think all my parts are basically fine.
- Stop competing!

448
00:26:17,400 --> 00:26:19,720
Can't we call for help?

449
00:26:19,840 --> 00:26:23,600
Yeah, cos the universe is quite small
and there's bound to be someone nearby/(!)

450
00:26:23,680 --> 00:26:26,560
Put these on, both of you.

451
00:26:28,560 --> 00:26:33,240
Oh, a poncho. The biggest crime
against fashion since lederhosen.

452
00:26:33,320 --> 00:26:36,040
Here we go!

453
00:26:36,120 --> 00:26:39,000
Pond and her boys...my poncho boys.

454
00:26:39,080 --> 00:26:41,560
If we're going to die, let's die
looking like a Peruvian folk band.

455
00:26:44,080 --> 00:26:45,840
We're not going to die.

456
00:26:45,960 --> 00:26:49,960
No, we're not, but our time's running out.
If we fall asleep here, we're in trouble.

457
00:26:50,040 --> 00:26:53,880
If we could divide up, then we'd have
an active presence in each world,

458
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:57,960
but the Dream Lord is switching us between
the worlds - why, why, what's the logic?

459
00:26:58,040 --> 00:26:59,600
Good idea, veggie.

460
00:26:59,640 --> 00:27:05,320
Let's divide you three up, so I can have
a little chat with our lovely companion.

461
00:27:05,440 --> 00:27:10,320
Maybe I'll keep her, and you can have
Pointy Nose to yourself for all eternity,

462
00:27:10,400 --> 00:27:12,360
should you manage to clamber aboard

463
00:27:12,440 --> 00:27:14,640
- some sort of reality.
- (BIRDSONG)

464
00:27:14,720 --> 00:27:16,920
- Can you hear that?
- What? No.

465
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:22,080
- Amy, don't be scared, we'll be back.
- (BIRDSONG GETS LOUDER)

466
00:27:22,160 --> 00:27:25,320
- Rory, Doctor, don't leave me.
- Amy...

467
00:27:25,400 --> 00:27:27,600
we're going to have fun, aren't we?

468
00:27:29,160 --> 00:27:31,760
No, please, not alone.

469
00:27:32,200 --> 00:27:35,400
(BANGING AND GLASS SMASHING)

470
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:40,360
(GRUNTS WITH EFFORT) Sorry.

471
00:27:41,680 --> 00:27:43,760
I'm sorry. Sorry...

472
00:27:48,720 --> 00:27:49,880
Sorry.

473
00:28:08,280 --> 00:28:09,800
(SIGHS)

474
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:15,240
(JINGLING)

475
00:28:44,480 --> 00:28:47,440
(SHRIEKING)

476
00:28:49,240 --> 00:28:51,040
OK, where is it?

477
00:29:00,360 --> 00:29:02,680
MAN: Help! Help, somebody!

478
00:29:02,760 --> 00:29:05,840
You couldn't live near
the shops, could you?

479
00:29:12,400 --> 00:29:13,880
It's OK, it's only me.

480
00:29:21,280 --> 00:29:23,600
Get in, get in, get in.
Quickly, quickly, over here.

481
00:29:23,680 --> 00:29:28,640
Quickly, come on, jump in.
Quick, get in now, quickly. Hurry up.

482
00:29:30,160 --> 00:29:31,880
Are we in?

483
00:29:33,240 --> 00:29:37,880
Come on, let's go, quickly,
all four, that's it, everyone in.

484
00:29:52,840 --> 00:29:54,640
DREAM LORD: Poor Amy.

485
00:29:54,720 --> 00:29:57,200
He always leaves you, doesn't he,

486
00:29:57,280 --> 00:30:00,360
alone in the dark?

487
00:30:00,440 --> 00:30:03,480
- Never apologises.
- He doesn't have to.

488
00:30:04,720 --> 00:30:06,200
That's good,

489
00:30:06,280 --> 00:30:08,080
because he never will.

490
00:30:09,320 --> 00:30:11,840
And now he's left you with me.

491
00:30:11,920 --> 00:30:15,800
Spooky, old, not-to-be-trusted me.

492
00:30:17,720 --> 00:30:19,400
Anything could happen.

493
00:30:22,280 --> 00:30:23,640
Who are you?

494
00:30:23,720 --> 00:30:26,600
And what do you want?

495
00:30:26,680 --> 00:30:29,800
The Doctor knows you,
but he's not telling me who you are.

496
00:30:29,880 --> 00:30:33,640
And he always does. Takes him
a while sometimes, but he tells me.

497
00:30:36,080 --> 00:30:37,800
So you're something different.

498
00:30:37,880 --> 00:30:41,680
Oh, is that who you think you are?
The one he trusts?

499
00:30:41,760 --> 00:30:43,320
Actually, yes.

500
00:30:43,400 --> 00:30:47,640
The only girl in the universe
to whom the Doctor tells everything?

501
00:30:50,320 --> 00:30:51,280
Yes.

502
00:30:51,360 --> 00:30:52,960
So what's his name?

503
00:30:55,760 --> 00:30:59,640
Now, which one of these men
would you really choose?

504
00:30:59,720 --> 00:31:01,640
Look at them.

505
00:31:01,720 --> 00:31:05,200
You ran away with a handsome hero.

506
00:31:05,280 --> 00:31:09,040
Would you really give him up
for a bumbling country doctor

507
00:31:09,120 --> 00:31:12,840
who thinks the only thing he needs
to be interesting is a ponytail?

508
00:31:12,920 --> 00:31:15,280
- Stop it!
- But maybe it's better

509
00:31:15,360 --> 00:31:17,560
than loving and losing the Doctor.

510
00:31:17,640 --> 00:31:22,320
Pick a world
and this nightmare will all be over.

511
00:31:22,400 --> 00:31:25,360
They'll listen to you.
It's you they're waiting for.

512
00:31:25,440 --> 00:31:26,960
Amy's men.

513
00:31:27,040 --> 00:31:28,520
Amy's choice.

514
00:31:50,360 --> 00:31:51,920
Everybody, out, out, out!

515
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:55,080
Into the church, that's right.
Don't answer the door.

516
00:32:01,760 --> 00:32:05,280
It's make-your-mind-up time
in both worlds.

517
00:32:05,360 --> 00:32:07,120
Bye. I need to find my friends.

518
00:32:07,200 --> 00:32:11,120
"Friends"? Is that the right word
for the people you acquire?

519
00:32:11,200 --> 00:32:14,320
Friends are people
you stay in touch with.

520
00:32:14,400 --> 00:32:17,400
Your friends never see you again
once they've grown up.

521
00:32:17,480 --> 00:32:21,680
The old man prefers the company
of the young, does he not?

522
00:32:45,200 --> 00:32:47,400
OK...

523
00:32:54,440 --> 00:32:56,760
(BANGING CONTINUES OUTSIDE)

524
00:33:00,200 --> 00:33:02,360
- How did I get up here?
- I carried you.

525
00:33:02,440 --> 00:33:04,760
I'm afraid you may experience
some bruising.

526
00:33:04,840 --> 00:33:06,520
- Where's the Doctor?
- I don't know.

527
00:33:06,600 --> 00:33:09,040
I want to do something for you.

528
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:30,000
I was starting to like it.

529
00:33:30,080 --> 00:33:32,360
(WINDOW SQUEAKS, AMY SQUEALS)

530
00:33:33,400 --> 00:33:35,600
Sorry, had to stop off at the butcher's.

531
00:33:37,920 --> 00:33:40,080
- What are we going to do?
- I don't know.

532
00:33:40,160 --> 00:33:42,800
I thought the freezing TARDIS was real,
but now I'm not so sure.

533
00:33:42,880 --> 00:33:45,680
Oh! I think the baby's starting.

534
00:33:45,760 --> 00:33:47,160
Honestly?

535
00:33:47,200 --> 00:33:50,120
- Would I make it up at a time like this?!
- Well, you do have a history of...

536
00:33:50,200 --> 00:33:51,960
being very lovely.

537
00:33:52,040 --> 00:33:54,720
- (AMY CRIES OUT)
- Why are they so desperate to kill us?

538
00:33:54,800 --> 00:33:56,440
They're scared.
Fear generates savagery.

539
00:34:01,840 --> 00:34:03,880
AMY: Rory!

540
00:34:09,080 --> 00:34:10,560
Rory!

541
00:34:13,960 --> 00:34:17,600
- No! I'm not ready.
- Stay.

542
00:34:17,680 --> 00:34:20,760
(DUST WHISPERS)

543
00:34:20,840 --> 00:34:22,880
Look after our baby.

544
00:34:29,760 --> 00:34:31,280
AMY: No.

545
00:34:31,360 --> 00:34:32,440
No.

546
00:34:33,920 --> 00:34:36,080
Come back.

547
00:34:41,120 --> 00:34:42,720
Save him.

548
00:34:42,800 --> 00:34:44,440
You save everyone. You always do.

549
00:34:44,520 --> 00:34:46,280
It's what you do.

550
00:34:46,360 --> 00:34:47,880
Not always.

551
00:34:51,480 --> 00:34:53,200
I'm sorry.

552
00:34:57,360 --> 00:35:00,840
Then what is the point of you?

553
00:35:18,120 --> 00:35:21,160
This is the dream.
Definitely, this one.

554
00:35:22,480 --> 00:35:25,920
Now, if we die here, we wake up, yeah?

555
00:35:28,080 --> 00:35:30,160
Unless we just die.

556
00:35:30,240 --> 00:35:34,440
Either way, this is my only chance
of seeing him again.

557
00:35:34,520 --> 00:35:37,640
- This is the dream.
- How do you know?

558
00:35:37,720 --> 00:35:42,440
Because if this is real life,
I don't want it. I don't want it.

559
00:35:50,600 --> 00:35:52,080
Why aren't they attacking?

560
00:35:52,120 --> 00:35:55,720
Either because this is just a dream, or
because they know what we're about to do.

561
00:36:03,400 --> 00:36:05,800
Be very sure.
This could be the real world.

562
00:36:05,880 --> 00:36:08,960
It can't be. Rory isn't here.

563
00:36:10,800 --> 00:36:14,960
I didn't know. I didn't, I didn't,
I honestly didn't, till right now.

564
00:36:17,400 --> 00:36:20,120
I just want him.

565
00:36:20,200 --> 00:36:22,080
OK.

566
00:36:27,360 --> 00:36:29,360
OK.

567
00:36:41,240 --> 00:36:45,200
I loved Rory, and I never told him,
but now he's gone.

568
00:36:48,920 --> 00:36:51,080
(ENGINE REVS)

569
00:37:49,680 --> 00:37:51,120
DREAM LORD: So...

570
00:37:51,200 --> 00:37:54,320
you chose this world.

571
00:37:55,880 --> 00:37:58,560
Well done. You got it right.

572
00:37:59,640 --> 00:38:02,320
And with only seconds left.

573
00:38:02,400 --> 00:38:05,360
Fair's fair. Let's warm you up.

574
00:38:06,800 --> 00:38:09,720
I hope you've enjoyed
your little fictions.

575
00:38:09,800 --> 00:38:15,360
It all came out of your imagination,
so I'll leave you to ponder on that.

576
00:38:15,440 --> 00:38:17,800
I have been defeated.

577
00:38:17,880 --> 00:38:20,400
I shall withdraw.

578
00:38:20,480 --> 00:38:21,960
Farewell.

579
00:38:36,280 --> 00:38:41,720
Something happened. I...
What happened to me?

580
00:38:41,800 --> 00:38:43,800
I...

581
00:38:43,880 --> 00:38:45,520
Oh.

582
00:38:45,600 --> 00:38:47,160
Oh, right.

583
00:38:47,240 --> 00:38:48,960
This is good.

584
00:38:49,040 --> 00:38:51,160
I am liking this.

585
00:38:51,240 --> 00:38:53,320
Was it something I said?

586
00:38:58,480 --> 00:39:01,640
Could you tell me what it was,
so I can use it in emergencies?

587
00:39:01,720 --> 00:39:04,040
And maybe birthdays.

588
00:39:04,120 --> 00:39:05,360
(BANG!)

589
00:39:05,440 --> 00:39:07,720
(METALLIC THRUMMING)

590
00:39:07,840 --> 00:39:12,040
- AMY: What are we doing now?
- Me? I'm going to blow up the TARDIS.

591
00:39:12,120 --> 00:39:13,960
What?

592
00:39:14,040 --> 00:39:16,360
Notice how helpful the Dream Lord was?

593
00:39:16,440 --> 00:39:18,320
OK, there was misinformation,
red herrings, malice,

594
00:39:18,400 --> 00:39:19,800
and I could have done
without the limerick.

595
00:39:19,840 --> 00:39:23,480
But he was always very keen to make us
choose between dream and reality.

596
00:39:23,560 --> 00:39:24,480
(BANGING)

597
00:39:24,560 --> 00:39:26,840
- (LAUGHS)
- What are you doing?!

598
00:39:26,920 --> 00:39:29,160
The Dream Lord conceded.
This isn't the dream!

599
00:39:29,240 --> 00:39:31,360
- Yes, it is!
- Stop him.

600
00:39:31,440 --> 00:39:33,560
Star burning cold? Do me a favour!

601
00:39:33,640 --> 00:39:38,200
The Dream Lord
has no power over the real world.

602
00:39:38,280 --> 00:39:40,760
He was offering us a choice
between two dreams.

603
00:39:40,840 --> 00:39:43,880
- How do you know that?
- Because I know who he is.

604
00:39:46,880 --> 00:39:49,800
(MONSTROUS EXPLOSION)

605
00:39:55,360 --> 00:39:57,760
(METALLIC THRUMMING)

606
00:40:00,120 --> 00:40:02,320
- Any questions?
- RORY: Hah!

607
00:40:02,400 --> 00:40:03,880
Um...

608
00:40:04,880 --> 00:40:06,360
What's that?

609
00:40:06,440 --> 00:40:10,240
A speck of psychic pollen from
the candle meadows of Karass don Slava.

610
00:40:10,320 --> 00:40:13,160
Must have been hanging around for ages.

611
00:40:13,240 --> 00:40:17,440
Fell in the time rotor, heated up
and induced a dream state for all of us.

612
00:40:31,120 --> 00:40:33,640
RORY: So that was the Dream Lord, then?

613
00:40:33,720 --> 00:40:35,160
Those little specks.

614
00:40:35,240 --> 00:40:37,280
No, no. No.

615
00:40:37,360 --> 00:40:40,080
Sorry, wasn't it obvious?
The Dream Lord was me.

616
00:40:40,160 --> 00:40:42,440
Psychic pollen,
it's a mind parasite.

617
00:40:42,520 --> 00:40:44,400
It feeds on everything dark in you.

618
00:40:44,480 --> 00:40:47,560
Gives it a voice,
turns it against you.

619
00:40:47,640 --> 00:40:50,600
I'm 907. It had a lot to go on.

620
00:40:50,680 --> 00:40:53,960
- But why didn't it feed on us, too?
- The darkness in you pair?

621
00:40:54,040 --> 00:40:56,080
It would've starved to death
in an instant.

622
00:40:56,160 --> 00:40:58,160
I choose my friends with great care.

623
00:40:58,280 --> 00:41:02,960
Otherwise I'm stuck with my own company,
and you know how that works out.

624
00:41:05,320 --> 00:41:07,800
But those things he said about you.

625
00:41:07,880 --> 00:41:10,160
You don't think any of that's true?

626
00:41:12,880 --> 00:41:15,520
Amy, right now a question
is about to occur to Rory.

627
00:41:15,600 --> 00:41:18,720
And seeing as the answer
is about to change his life,

628
00:41:18,800 --> 00:41:20,960
I think you should give him
your full attention.

629
00:41:23,120 --> 00:41:25,840
- Yeah. Actually, yeah.
- There it is.

630
00:41:25,920 --> 00:41:28,280
What I don't get is
you blew up the TARDIS,

631
00:41:28,400 --> 00:41:31,080
that stopped that dream,
but what stopped the Leadworth dream?

632
00:41:31,160 --> 00:41:35,120
- We crashed the camper van.
- Oh, right. I don't remember that bit.

633
00:41:35,200 --> 00:41:37,360
No, you weren't there.
You were already...

634
00:41:37,440 --> 00:41:38,600
Already what?

635
00:41:40,160 --> 00:41:43,200
Dead. You died in that dream.
Mrs Poggit got you.

636
00:41:44,360 --> 00:41:46,680
OK.

637
00:41:46,760 --> 00:41:50,240
But how did you know it was a dream,
before you crashed the van?

638
00:41:50,320 --> 00:41:52,960
How did you know
you wouldn't just die?

639
00:41:54,720 --> 00:41:56,280
I didn't.

640
00:41:58,400 --> 00:41:59,640
Oh.

641
00:41:59,720 --> 00:42:01,600
Yeah.

642
00:42:01,680 --> 00:42:03,240
Oh.

643
00:42:03,320 --> 00:42:06,160
- Yeah, "Oh".
- (RORY LAUGHS NERVOUSLY)

644
00:42:18,880 --> 00:42:20,360
So...

645
00:42:21,600 --> 00:42:24,280
Well, then, where now?

646
00:42:24,400 --> 00:42:27,560
Or should I just pop down
to the swimming pool for a few lengths?

647
00:42:27,640 --> 00:42:31,280
I don't know. Anywhere's good for me.

648
00:42:31,360 --> 00:42:33,440
I'm happy anywhere.

649
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:36,520
It's up to Amy this time.

650
00:42:36,600 --> 00:42:38,600
Amy's choice.

